>
  <p>
    Most mosquito species don't travel far — many stay within a few hundred feet
    of where they hatched for their entire lives. That's genuinely good news: it
    means your mosquito problem is mostly a <em>local</em> problem, and local
    problems can be solved. Here's the order that actually works.
  </p>

  <h2>Step 1: Eliminate standing water (this is 80% of the job)</h2>
  <p>
    A mosquito goes from egg to biting adult in about <strong>7 to 10 days</strong>,
    and it only needs a surprisingly small amount of still water to do it — a
    bottle cap's worth is enough for some species. Walk your property and empty
    anything holding water:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Clogged gutters</strong> — the single most-missed breeding site on most properties</li>
    <li><strong>Plant saucers</strong> under pots on decks and patios</li>
    <li><strong>Birdbaths and pet bowls</strong> — fine to keep, just refresh every few days</li>
    <li><strong>Tarps, covers, and sagging pool covers</strong> holding pockets of rain</li>
    <li><strong>Children's toys, wheelbarrows, buckets, old tires</strong></li>
    <li><strong>Corrugated downspout extensions</strong>, which hold water in every ridge</li>
    <li><strong>Low spots in the lawn</strong> that stay wet for more than a few days</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Because of that 7-to-10-day cycle, doing this walk <strong>once a week</strong>
    during summer breaks the breeding cycle before a new generation can emerge.
    It's free, and it outperforms every gadget you can buy.
  </p>

  <h2>Step 2: Treat the water you can't remove</h2>
  <p>
    Rain barrels, ponds, ditches, and drains have to hold water. For those, use
    <strong>Bti</strong> (<em>Bacillus thuringiensis israelensis</em>) — sold as
    mosquito dunks or bits. It's a naturally-occurring bacterium that kills
    mosquito larvae and is considered safe for pets, birds, fish, and wildlife.
    One dunk typically treats a container for around 30 days. This is the highest
    value-per-dollar product in the entire category.
  </p>

  <h2>Step 3: Make the space less hospitable</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Move air.</strong> Mosquitoes are weak fliers — a simple oscillating
      outdoor fan on a patio is remarkably effective and also disperses the CO2
      plume they home in on.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Cut the shade and damp.</strong> Trim tall grass and dense
      groundcover where adults rest during the heat of the day.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Improve drainage</strong> in the chronically soggy corner rather
      than fighting it every summer.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Step 4: Add a device for the space you actually use</h2>
  <p>
    With breeding under control, a trap or zapper is doing the job it's good at —
    reducing the adults in the specific area where you sit — rather than fighting
    an endless supply. Match the device to the space: silent fan-and-sticky traps
    for indoors and bedrooms, CO2-style traps for targeted outdoor mosquito
    reduction, UV zappers for broad flying-insect control on patios. We break
    down which is which in our
    <a href="/blog/bug-zapper-vs-mosquito-trap/">zapper vs trap comparison</a>, and
    rank the specific models in our
    <a href="/reviews/best-mosquito-zappers/">best mosquito zappers and traps guide</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>What doesn't work (save your money)</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Ultrasonic repellers.</strong> Repeated independent testing has
      found no meaningful effect on mosquitoes. Skip them.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Citronella candles, alone.</strong> They produce a small effect in
      still air right beside the candle, and essentially nothing in a breeze.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Bug zappers as a mosquito-only solution.</strong> UV light is a
      great general flying-insect attractant, but mosquitoes hunt primarily by
      carbon dioxide and body heat. A zapper will catch some, but it's not the
      most targeted tool for mosquitoes specifically — which is exactly why
      CO2-based traps exist.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Bat houses and "mosquito-repelling" plants.</strong> Pleasant
      additions to a yard; negligible as mosquito control.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The realistic outcome</h2>
  <p>
    You will not get to zero mosquitoes — anyone promising that is selling
    something. What you can absolutely do is take a yard that's unusable at dusk
    and make it comfortable: source elimination weekly, Bti in the water you keep,
    airflow where you sit, and one well-matched device for the patio. That
    combination is what actually gives you your evenings back.
  </p>
